71.5	Clostridium_difficile	Clostridium difficile	Clostridium difficile (from the Greek kloster (κλωστήρ), spindle, and Latin difficile, difficult), also known as "CDF/cdf", or "C. diff", is a species of Gram-positive bacteria of the genus Clostridium that causes severe diarrhea and other intestinal disease when competing bacteria in the gut flora have been wiped out by antibiotics.	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0f/Clostridium_difficile_01.png/220px-Clostridium_difficile_01.png
